AGI - Russian leadership should drastically strengthen the "containment and deterrence policy" > and lead a "demonstrative nuclear explosion" to stop further involvement of the West in the war in Ukraine > . It is the invitation contained in an article by Dmitri Suslov>, Deputy Director of Research Programmes of the Centre for European and International Studies at the Moscow Higher School of Economics and considered one of the most influential Kremlin advisers on foreign policy issues. The Centre is headed by the Serghei Karaganov polythologist, who advises the presidential administration.
&nbsp;
In an analysis on Profil's head, he argues that if one does not proceed with such a move, "a real 'non-cold' &nbsp war; between Russia and NATO will become inevitable" and "will surely arrive at the nuclear level" because of the superiority of the United States and their allies in the field of conventional weapons. Suslov noted that the Atlantic Alliance countries are already ready to "delete one of the "clearest red lines" allowing Kiev to attack Russia with Western weapons. And soon you could get to the point that NATO will clear regular troops in Ukraine and begin to break down the Russian missiles, warns the analyst.
&nbsp;
For Suslov, Russia must show in advance that it awaits a harsh response. "To confirm the seriousness of intentions and convince our opponents that we are ready for an escalation, it is worth considering conducting a demonstration nuclear explosion (i.e. not a fight)", he said. According to him, "the political and psychological effect of the atomic fungus, which will be broadcast live on all TV channels in the world", will bring Western politicians back to the "nuclear war fear".
&nbsp;
Subsequently, in a commentary on the Russian Rbc test, Suslov clarified that the "demonstration nuclear explosion" should be carried out on the Russian territory or in a neutral area. As a possible option suggested Novaya Zemlya, where the Urss tested such weapons until 1990. According to Suslov, there is no mention of a nuclear explosion above or within Ukraine or "on the territory of some third State".&nbsp;

